Malaria Detection - Final Submission¶

Project Recap¶

In the previous 2 milestones we have looked at the context of the problem of Malaria contageon. We have looked at building an efficient computer vision model to detect malaria. We have used convolutional neural network to effectively identify malaria infected cells with a 89% recall, 98% precision and 93% f1-score on the test set. We will finalize this by seeing if we could improve our score with automated parameter tuning methods and also transfer learning. The following four models highlights these methods.

Context¶

Malaria is a contagious disease caused by Plasmodium parasites that are transmitted to humans through the bites of infected female Anopheles mosquitoes. The parasites enter the blood and begin damaging red blood cells (RBCs) that carry oxygen, which can result in respiratory distress and other complications. The lethal parasites can stay alive for more than a year in a person’s body without showing any symptoms. Therefore, late treatment can cause complications and could even be fatal. Almost 50% of the world’s population is in danger from malaria. There were more than 229 million malaria cases and 400,000 malaria-related deaths reported over the world in 2019. Children under 5 years of age are the most vulnerable population group affected by malaria; in 2019 they accounted for 67% of all malaria deaths worldwide.

Traditional diagnosis of malaria in the laboratory requires careful inspection by an experienced professional to discriminate between healthy and infected red blood cells. It is a tedious, time-consuming process, and the diagnostic accuracy (which heavily depends on human expertise) can be adversely impacted by inter-observer variability.

An automated system can help with the early and accurate detection of malaria. Applications of automated classification techniques using Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) have consistently shown higher accuracy than manual classification. It would therefore be highly beneficial to propose a method that performs malaria detection using Deep Learning Algorithms.

The Issue¶

As we can see, there has consistently been over 250 million cases of Malaria every year. Over 90% is in the African region. As noted above, 2019 reported 229 million malaria cases and 400,000 malaria-related deaths reported over the world.

  • Time issue: If a physician can visually diagnose 60 cases an hour. He will only be able to get to 120,000 cases a year if he does nothing else. At this rate, you'll need about 1,900 doctors working full-time all year round just to diagnose the cases in 2019. This doesn't seem like a large number, but where can you find 1,900 doctors who can commit to diagnosing 120,000 cases a year.
  • If you can find someone dedicate 10 hours hours a week, he will be able to get to 30,000 cases a year. Then you will need 7,633 doctor to get the job done.
  • Cost issue: The national average hourly rate for a physician is about 100/hr which works out to be 380 million dollars annually.
  • An efficient computer model could potentially scan maybe 60,000 cases an hour depending on the efficiency of the algorithm and/or processing power. A single computer could handle 229 million cases in just 201 days. And it doesn't need any coffee.

Advantages¶

  • Alleviates huge cost and labor burden.
  • Frees up time and mental power to creatively tackle the issues.
  • Saves lives.

Objective¶

Build an efficient computer vision model to detect malaria. The model should identify whether the image of a red blood cell is that of one infected with malaria or not, and classify the same as parasitized or uninfected, respectively.

About the dataset¶

There are a total of 24,958 train and 2,600 test images (colored) with an equal number of parasitized and uninfected instances, where:

  • The parasitized cells contain the Plasmodium parasite
  • The uninfected cells are free of the Plasmodium parasites but could contain other impurities

#We will run the same code for "parasitized" as well as "uninfected" folders within the "train" folder
for folder_name in ['/parasitized/', '/uninfected/']:
    
    #Path of the folder
    images_path = os.listdir(train_dir + folder_name)

    for i, image_name in enumerate(images_path):
        try:
            #Opening each image using the path of that image
            image = Image.open(train_dir + folder_name + image_name)

            #Resizing each image to (64,64)
            image = image.resize((SIZE, SIZE))

            #Converting images to arrays and appending that array to the empty list defined above
            train_images.append(np.array(image))

            #Creating labels for parasitized and uninfected images
            if folder_name=='/parasitized/':
                train_labels.append(1)
            else:
                train_labels.append(0)
        except Exception:
            pass       

#Converting lists to arrays
train_images = np.array(train_images)
train_labels = np.array(train_labels)

Proposed Approach¶

  • POTENTIAL TECHNIQUES An automated system can help with the early and accurate detection of malaria. Applications of automated classification techniques using Machine Learning (ML) and Artificial Intelligence (AI) have consistently shown higher accuracy than manual classification. It would therefore be highly beneficial to propose a method that performs malaria detection using Deep Learning Algorithms.
  • OVERALL SOLUTION DESIGN We will be using building a convolution neural network (CNN) model to classify between infected and non-infected blood cell samples from the images. This is a binary classification problem so we will be using a sigmoid activation function. Our process will be Data Preparation-> Exploratory Data analysis-> Model Building-> Model evaluation-> Model selection-> Summary of potential benefits-> Recommendation for implementation.
  • MEASURES OF SUCCESS We will attempt various models and test accuracy with a loss score. We will also use a 20% validation split for each model to see if training and validation accuracy improve together to determine if the model is overfitting.

Defining our hypermodel¶

In [126]:
def build_model(hp):  # random search passes this hyperparameter() object 
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    
    model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int('input_units',
                                min_value=16,
                                max_value=160,
                                step=16), (3, 3), padding="same", input_shape=train_images_n.shape[1:]))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout',
                    min_value=0.0,
                    max_value=0.9,
                    step=0.1)))

    for i in range(hp.Int('n_layers', 1, 4)):  # adding variation of layers.
        model.add(Conv2D(hp.Int(f'conv_{i}_units',
                                min_value=32,
                                max_value=256,
                                step=32), (3, 3), padding="same",))
        model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
        model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
        model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout',
                    min_value=0.0,
                    max_value=0.9,
                    step=0.1)))
        
    model.add(Flatten()) 
    
    model.add(Dense(hp.Int('input_units',
                                min_value=16,
                                max_value=160,
                                step=16)))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(alpha=0.1))
    model.add(Dropout(hp.Float('dropout',
                    min_value=0.0,
                    max_value=0.9,
                    step=0.1)))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))

    adam = optimizers.Adam(
        learning_rate=tf.Variable(0.001),
        beta_1=tf.Variable(0.9),
        beta_2=tf.Variable(0.999),
        epsilon=tf.Variable(1e-7))
    adam.iterations
    adam.decay = tf.Variable(0.0)
    
    model.compile(
        loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
        optimizer = adam,
        metrics = ['accuracy'])

    return model

Random Search¶

The Random Search hyperparameter tuning method randomly tries a combination of hyperparameters from a given search space.

Observations¶

  • We did three three hyperparameter tuning methods to tune the number of layers, node size per layer and dropout rates, to find the best model architecture.
  • Out of the three hyperparameter tuning methods we found that Random Search and Bayesian Optimization did the best at around 95% accuracy while hyperband only achieved 76%
  • It's interesting that both Random Search and Bayesian Optimization had very similar model architecture. So we will look at these final 2 to see which performs better. We will be tuning the optimal learning rate and number of epochs with the next model.

from tensorflow.keras import losses

#Define the function
def cnn_model_1():
    model = Sequential() 
    #Add layers as per the architecture mentioned above
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters=112, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters=160, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    
    model.add(Flatten())
    
    model.add(Dense(112))
    model.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model.add(Dropout(0.3))
    model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    
    #declare adam optimizer with learning rate of 0.001 
    adam = optimizers.Adam()
    
    #compile the model
    model.compile(
        loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
        optimizer = adam,
        metrics = ['accuracy'])
    
    return model

# Let's test out different learning rate for each epoch to discover what's the best learning rate
lr_scheduler = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lambda epoch: 1e-4 * 10**(epoch/8))

# Prepping our model before we save it out
from tensorflow.keras.models import Model
from tensorflow.python.keras.layers import deserialize, serialize
from tensorflow.python.keras.saving import saving_utils

def unpack(model, training_config, weights):
    restored_model = deserialize(model)
    
    if training_config is not None:
        restored_model.compile(**saving_utils.compile_args_from_training_config(
        training_config))
    
    restored_model.set_weights(weights)
    
    return restored_model

def make_keras_picklable():

    def __reduce__(self):
        model_metadata = saving_utils.model_metadata(self)
        training_config = model_metadata.get("training_config", None)
        model = serialize(self)
        weights = self.get_weights()
        return (unpack, (model, training_config, weights))

    cls = Model
    cls.__reduce__ = __reduce__
    
# Run the function
make_keras_picklable()

#Define the function
def cnn_model_2():
    model_2 = Sequential() 
    
    #Adding our layers
    model_2.add(Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding="same", input_shape=(64, 64, 3)))
    model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model_2.add(Dropout(0.4))
    
    model_2.add(Conv2D(filters=160, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model_2.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model_2.add(Dropout(0.4))
    
    model_2.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model_2.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model_2.add(Dropout(0.4))
    
    model_2.add(Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3, 3), padding='same'))
    model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model_2.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    model_2.add(Dropout(0.4))
    
    model_2.add(Flatten())
    
    model_2.add(Dense(128))
    model_2.add(LeakyReLU(0.1))
    model_2.add(Dropout(0.4))
    model_2.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    
    #declare adam optimizer with learning rate of 0.001
    adam = optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=0.001)
    
    #compile the model
    model_2.compile(
        loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
        optimizer = adam,
        metrics = ['accuracy'])
    
    return model_2

Model 3 - Transfer Learning Model¶

Transfer learning is a popular deep learning technique that reuses a pre-trained model on a new problem. It can train deep neural networks with comparatively little data. This is very useful in the data science field since most real-world problems typically do not have millions of labeled data points to train complex models.

Let's begin by clearing the backend and fixing the seed.

We will use VGG16 as the pre-trained model. You can read about it here.

Also, we will use the Functional Model API to build the model this time because it allows explicitly connecting the output of one layer to the input of another layer. Each connection is specified. You can read about it here.

In [236]:
#Importing necessary libraries
from tensorflow.keras import Model
from tensorflow.keras.applications.vgg16 import VGG16

Now, let's instantiate the VGG16 model.

  • The VGG16 model was originally trained on images of size 224 x 224. The TensorFlow application allows the minimum image size of 32x32 which fortunately is smaller than the image size of our dataset. We will change the size of the input image to 64x64.
  • By specifying the argument include_top=False argument, we load a network that doesn't include the classification layers at the top i.e. we will use the VGG16 model only for feature extraction.

def build_tf_model(hp):  # random search passes this hyperparameter() object 
    
    
    x = Flatten()(transfer_layer.output) #Flatten the output from the 3rd block of the VGG16 model
    x = Dense(hp.Int('input_units',
                     min_value=16,
                     max_value=160,
                     step=16), 
              activation = LeakyReLU(.1))(x)
    
    x = Dropout(hp.Float('dropout',
                    min_value=0.0,
                    max_value=0.9,
                    step=0.1))(x)

    pred = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')(x)

    model = Model(vgg_model.input, pred) #Initializing the model

    adam = optimizers.Adam(
        learning_rate=tf.Variable(0.001),
        beta_1=tf.Variable(0.9),
        beta_2=tf.Variable(0.999),
        epsilon=tf.Variable(1e-7))
    adam.iterations
    adam.decay = tf.Variable(0.0)
    
    model.compile(
        loss = 'binary_crossentropy', 
        optimizer = adam,
        metrics = ['accuracy'])
    
    return model

Executive Summary¶

  • Time Savings: A single physician diagnosing 60 cases an hour will be able to get to 120,000 cases a year if he does nothing else, he will need to work for 1,900 years just to diagnose the cases in 2019 alone.
  • Cost issue: We noted that it costs approximately 380 million dollars annually in manhours to handle the cases in 2019 alone.
  • An efficient computer model presents a huge time and cost saving and a single computer could do the job in just 201 days at a rate of 60,000 cases per hour. These in itself is a good reason for the project.
  • But the most important reason is that it will save lives. 400,000 lives in 2019 alone.

Problem and Solution Summary¶

  • In previous milestone we were able to build a pretty robust convolutional neural network to effectively identify malaria infected cells with a 89% recall, 98% precision and 93% f1-score on the test set.
  • In this notebook we finalize looked at some automated parameter tuning methods and also transfer learning and we saw slight improvement in our scores.
  • Hyperparameter tuning is an effective method to find the best model architecture for machine learning problems and should be done early in the model building process.
  • Transfer Learning can also be an effective method to use pretrained models on new problems, however, it requires some adjustments as well. There may also be issues of overfitting to resolve - this seems to be true in our case.

Solution¶

  • As noted above, The Bayesian Optimized Model (2) presents a robust and efficient model with a high accuracy rate with a 93% recall, 97% precision and 95% f1-score on the test set.
  • The greater improvement in the recall score means we will get less false negative.
  • The model could, of course, continue to improve with more tuning but, at the current rate it can be deployed.

Recommendations for Implementation¶

  • The model requires images to be taken in a color format that can be converted to 64x64 image.
  • It is recommended that a physician or trained health professional examine the scan following detection of malaria infection by the model to confirm accuracy of diagnosis.
  • The model should be periodically retrained with new data to maintain accuracy.
